1
00:00:08,166 --> 00:00:10,541
[WOMAN]
February 18th, 2055.

2
00:00:10,625 --> 00:00:11,583
♪

3
00:00:11,666 --> 00:00:13,791
Researcher, Angelica Klein.

4
00:00:14,833 --> 00:00:18,916
Automata, model DZNA 2058.

5
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:20,583
Experiment objective,

6
00:00:20,666 --> 00:00:22,208
engage in dialogue,

7
00:00:22,291 --> 00:00:24,958
in order to create an automaton
with a personality.

8
00:00:28,291 --> 00:00:29,208
[sigh]

9
00:00:29,291 --> 00:00:30,791
[heavy breathing]

10
00:00:32,166 --> 00:00:33,583
[MAN]
Angelica.

11
00:00:33,666 --> 00:00:34,750
Huh?

12
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:38,250
[MAN]
Are you nervous?

13
00:00:38,333 --> 00:00:39,583
[sigh]
Yes.

14
00:00:40,583 --> 00:00:43,125
[ANGELICA] I’m just not used
to this sort of situation.

15
00:00:43,208 --> 00:00:45,666
But, don’t worry about me,
it’ll be fine.

16
00:00:45,750 --> 00:00:48,916
[MAN] That device on your finger
is monitoring your vitals.

17
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:50,333
It’s locking down the Automata

18
00:00:50,416 --> 00:00:51,916
because it’s
detecting your unease.

19
00:00:52,916 --> 00:00:54,791
[ANGELICA] Of course I’m uneasy.
I’m being stared at.

20
00:00:54,875 --> 00:00:56,625
[chuckle]

21
00:00:56,708 --> 00:00:58,291
[MAN]
Fair enough.

22
00:00:58,375 --> 00:01:00,625
If you’re able to joke around,
you’re probably alright.

23
00:01:00,708 --> 00:01:04,208
I just adjusted the threshold.
It can boot up now.

24
00:01:04,291 --> 00:01:06,375
I’m ready whenever you are.

25
00:01:06,458 --> 00:01:09,500
[MAN] Any abnormalities,
and we shut it down.

26
00:01:09,583 --> 00:01:10,875
[ANGELICA]
No.

27
00:01:10,958 --> 00:01:12,833
I’m going to see this
experiment through.

28
00:01:14,125 --> 00:01:16,208
[MAN]
Very well. Then, please begin.

29
00:01:17,500 --> 00:01:19,875
Well, 2058,

30
00:01:19,958 --> 00:01:22,250
how do you feel? Tell me.

31
00:01:23,291 --> 00:01:24,875
-[electronic noise]
-[robotic voice] Feelings.

32
00:01:24,958 --> 00:01:27,541
Emotions. Moods.

33
00:01:27,625 --> 00:01:29,708
I do not understand
these things.

34
00:01:29,791 --> 00:01:31,000
Tell me.

35
00:01:31,083 --> 00:01:33,750
♪

36
00:01:35,166 --> 00:01:36,958
[DONNA]
Tell you?

37
00:01:39,208 --> 00:01:41,208
Tell you what?

38
00:01:41,291 --> 00:01:43,041
How I’m feeling right now?

39
00:01:43,125 --> 00:01:44,375
Jealous.

40
00:01:44,458 --> 00:01:46,291
Are they trying
to steal it again?

41
00:01:47,291 --> 00:01:49,791
Steal it? Steal what?

42
00:01:51,166 --> 00:01:53,833
Pain. Steal pain?

43
00:01:53,916 --> 00:01:56,083
Do I need to swap my parts?

44
00:01:56,166 --> 00:01:58,541
No. This pain is mine.

45
00:01:58,625 --> 00:02:00,916
I won’t let anyone have it.

46
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:02,041
[grunt]

47
00:02:04,666 --> 00:02:05,708
[grunt]

48
00:02:05,791 --> 00:02:08,000
-[crunch]
-[growl]

49
00:03:38,458 --> 00:03:40,916
-[jet engines roar]
-[DONNA] What a joke.

50
00:03:41,916 --> 00:03:44,375
Are you under the illusion
that you own me now?

51
00:03:46,791 --> 00:03:49,666
The date is March 4th, 2055.

52
00:03:49,750 --> 00:03:52,125
Researcher, Angelica Klein.

53
00:03:52,208 --> 00:03:54,583
Experiment day 14.

54
00:03:54,666 --> 00:03:55,500
♪

55
00:03:55,583 --> 00:03:57,000
How do you feel right now?

56
00:03:57,083 --> 00:03:59,125
[less robotic sounding]
That question once again?

57
00:03:59,208 --> 00:04:02,041
That’s right. Always the same.

58
00:04:02,125 --> 00:04:05,125
It helps me to monitor how
you change from day to day.

59
00:04:05,208 --> 00:04:08,083
[2058]
Monitor... what, exactly?

60
00:04:08,166 --> 00:04:10,125
[ANGELICA]
Your development.

61
00:04:10,208 --> 00:04:12,333
You’ve become quite human-like.

62
00:04:12,416 --> 00:04:14,416
And not just in your appearance.

63
00:04:15,875 --> 00:04:17,208
I see.

64
00:04:17,291 --> 00:04:19,000
And your monitoring
told you that?

65
00:04:19,083 --> 00:04:21,083
I don’t need monitoring
for that last part.

66
00:04:21,166 --> 00:04:22,333
Oh?

67
00:04:22,416 --> 00:04:24,708
I don’t understand.
Please tell me.

68
00:04:24,791 --> 00:04:26,666
Ah, that question again?

69
00:04:26,750 --> 00:04:29,208
That’s right. Always the same.

70
00:04:29,291 --> 00:04:31,958
Okay, enough.
We’ll drop the subject there.

71
00:04:33,875 --> 00:04:36,375
For today, let’s use this paper.

72
00:04:39,708 --> 00:04:42,000
Experiment day 15.

73
00:04:42,083 --> 00:04:43,625
How’re you feeling today?

74
00:04:43,708 --> 00:04:45,750
[more human] I want to learn
things about you, Angelica.

75
00:04:45,833 --> 00:04:49,416
Where did you come from?
What is your family?

76
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:50,625
[ANGELICA]
I was born somewhere

77
00:04:50,708 --> 00:04:52,500
with a much warmer
climate than here.

78
00:04:52,583 --> 00:04:55,875
As for my family...
What do you think family is?

79
00:04:55,958 --> 00:04:57,125
[2058]
Family.

80
00:04:57,208 --> 00:04:59,875
Parents, children, siblings.

81
00:04:59,958 --> 00:05:02,125
A group of people
connected by blood.

82
00:05:02,208 --> 00:05:04,041
-[cutting]
-[gasp]

83
00:05:05,041 --> 00:05:06,041
Wait, what are you doing?

84
00:05:06,125 --> 00:05:08,708
♪

85
00:05:08,791 --> 00:05:09,791
What?

86
00:05:11,041 --> 00:05:12,083
[gasp]

87
00:05:13,666 --> 00:05:15,833
[2058]
This is your family, is it not?

88
00:05:15,916 --> 00:05:17,250
[ANGELICA gasps]

89
00:05:17,333 --> 00:05:20,583
[2058] Your pulse has risen,
Angelica. Why?

90
00:05:22,041 --> 00:05:23,625
You shouldn’t do that.

91
00:05:23,708 --> 00:05:25,583
Cutting a person with scissors.

92
00:05:25,666 --> 00:05:27,125
[2058]
It is a picture.

93
00:05:27,208 --> 00:05:28,708
Well, maybe so,

94
00:05:28,791 --> 00:05:31,083
-but it’s more than that!
-[2058] How can that be?

95
00:05:31,166 --> 00:05:32,708
I do not understand.

96
00:05:32,791 --> 00:05:35,083
-This is a representation.
-Stop it!

97
00:05:36,416 --> 00:05:38,250
[2058]
What is wrong, Angelica?

98
00:05:39,250 --> 00:05:41,791
[ANGELICA] Enough.
Let’s drop this subject for now.

99
00:05:44,833 --> 00:05:47,750
[water running]

100
00:05:50,458 --> 00:05:51,791
[ANGELICA]
Are you nervous?

101
00:05:52,791 --> 00:05:53,666
[gasp]

102
00:05:55,791 --> 00:05:58,291
[2058, distorted]
How are you feeling right now?

103
00:05:58,375 --> 00:05:59,666
[drip]

104
00:06:04,166 --> 00:06:05,625
Why are you dressed like that?

105
00:06:05,708 --> 00:06:07,750
[more human sounding]
Why are you asking?

106
00:06:07,833 --> 00:06:09,916
What happened to
your usual question?

107
00:06:11,250 --> 00:06:13,916
Date, March 6th, 2055.

108
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,208
Researcher, Angelica Klein.

109
00:06:16,291 --> 00:06:18,125
Experiment day 16.

110
00:06:18,208 --> 00:06:19,708
How do you feel right now?

111
00:06:19,791 --> 00:06:22,041
What about you, Angelica?

112
00:06:22,125 --> 00:06:25,041
Should we stop?
You don’t seem like yourself.

113
00:06:25,125 --> 00:06:26,750
[ANGELICA]
No, I’m fine.

114
00:06:26,833 --> 00:06:28,875
Now, tell me how you’re feeling.

115
00:06:28,958 --> 00:06:30,375
Very well.

116
00:06:30,458 --> 00:06:32,208
I feel I want to continue
yesterday’s discussion.

117
00:06:32,291 --> 00:06:34,000
-[ANGELICA gasps]
-Regarding your family.

118
00:06:35,583 --> 00:06:37,000
What about them?

119
00:06:37,083 --> 00:06:39,458
[2058] Your father,
mother, and one sibling.

120
00:06:39,541 --> 00:06:41,250
Your family name is Klein.

121
00:06:41,333 --> 00:06:43,041
That’s right.

122
00:06:43,125 --> 00:06:45,250
[2058] What is your
father’s full name?

123
00:06:45,333 --> 00:06:48,375
My father’s name? Jan Klein.

124
00:06:50,625 --> 00:06:53,416
And my father’s name
is Jacques Yvain?

125
00:06:54,416 --> 00:06:56,208
[ANGELICA]
Technically. Jacques is called

126
00:06:56,291 --> 00:06:57,916
the father of all Automata,

127
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,583
including DZs like you.

128
00:07:00,666 --> 00:07:03,125
But, I am not an Yvain,
is this correct?

129
00:07:03,208 --> 00:07:06,083
[ANGELICA] Yes. It’s not
quite like having family.

130
00:07:06,166 --> 00:07:09,750
And was Jan Klein the one who
gave you the name Angelica?

131
00:07:09,833 --> 00:07:13,000
Well, I think my mother
and father named me together.

132
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,541
Jacques Yvain did not
give me a name, however.

133
00:07:16,625 --> 00:07:17,666
[ANGELICA]
What?

134
00:07:17,750 --> 00:07:20,791
[2058]
I am called 2058.

135
00:07:20,875 --> 00:07:22,666
That is the name of my body.

136
00:07:22,750 --> 00:07:25,500
It is not the name of my will.

137
00:07:25,583 --> 00:07:27,166
Your will?

138
00:07:27,250 --> 00:07:29,250
Yes. In here.

139
00:07:29,333 --> 00:07:30,250
Uh--

140
00:07:31,375 --> 00:07:32,958
Then, how about this?

141
00:07:33,041 --> 00:07:36,125
Today, we can think up
a name for you, together!

142
00:07:36,208 --> 00:07:37,750
[2058]
No.

143
00:07:37,833 --> 00:07:39,625
-I already know my true name.
-[gasp]

144
00:07:39,708 --> 00:07:41,208
♪

145
00:07:41,291 --> 00:07:43,958
What else could it
be but Angelica?

146
00:07:44,041 --> 00:07:46,041
Uh-- What do you mean?

147
00:07:46,125 --> 00:07:47,708
Angelica is my name!

148
00:07:47,791 --> 00:07:49,916
Yes, and it is mine as well.

149
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:53,166
Which is only natural as I was
made to copy your personality.

150
00:07:53,250 --> 00:07:54,875
You’re not supposed
to be a copy.

151
00:07:54,958 --> 00:07:56,375
You have your own personality--

152
00:07:56,458 --> 00:07:57,958
[2058]
I am a copy.

153
00:07:58,041 --> 00:08:00,166
I was programmed to be that way.

154
00:08:00,250 --> 00:08:01,958
Why did you think you came here?

155
00:08:02,041 --> 00:08:04,208
It was to give me a personality.

156
00:08:04,291 --> 00:08:06,166
To give me “Angelica.”

157
00:08:06,250 --> 00:08:08,958
Not true. I am me,

158
00:08:09,041 --> 00:08:11,875
and you’re you. That’s why--

159
00:08:11,958 --> 00:08:15,291
I am Angelica. And you are...

160
00:08:16,291 --> 00:08:17,541
Ha!

161
00:08:17,625 --> 00:08:19,458
How do you feel about
the name “Donna?”

162
00:08:19,541 --> 00:08:21,375
A personality
transplant “donor.”

163
00:08:21,458 --> 00:08:23,041
[ANGELICA]
Transplant?

164
00:08:23,125 --> 00:08:24,958
[heavy breathing]

165
00:08:25,041 --> 00:08:26,666
[lights buzzing]

166
00:08:26,750 --> 00:08:28,125
-No!
-[smash]

167
00:08:28,208 --> 00:08:29,791
-I am Angelica!
-[snap]

168
00:08:29,875 --> 00:08:31,500
I won’t give my
identity to you!

169
00:08:31,583 --> 00:08:33,541
[panting]

170
00:08:33,625 --> 00:08:34,958
[grunt]

171
00:08:35,041 --> 00:08:37,583
[MAN] Angelica,
I’m stopping the experiment.

172
00:08:37,666 --> 00:08:38,791
♪

173
00:08:38,875 --> 00:08:40,500
[ANGELICA]
I won’t give up Angelica.

174
00:08:40,583 --> 00:08:42,416
I won’t give it up,
do you hear me?!

175
00:08:42,500 --> 00:08:44,791
Not to the likes of you! Never!

176
00:08:44,875 --> 00:08:46,083
-[tearing]
-[gasp]

177
00:08:46,166 --> 00:08:48,708
[MAN]
Angelica! Listen to me!

178
00:08:49,708 --> 00:08:52,083
Your vital signs are
over the threshold.

179
00:08:52,166 --> 00:08:54,750
I’m shutting down 2058 now!

180
00:08:54,833 --> 00:08:56,666
The experiment is canceled.

181
00:08:58,000 --> 00:08:59,583
[sigh]
It’s alright.

182
00:09:00,583 --> 00:09:02,083
I can go on.

183
00:09:03,250 --> 00:09:04,458
[MAN]
It’s over.

184
00:09:04,541 --> 00:09:06,875
[ANGELICA]
I’m fine, I swear.

185
00:09:07,875 --> 00:09:09,750
[MAN]
Let’s call it a day for now.

186
00:09:10,750 --> 00:09:12,916
[ANGELICA]
I’m sorry. See you tomorrow.

187
00:09:14,333 --> 00:09:15,833
I want to see this through.

188
00:09:15,916 --> 00:09:17,333
Are you Donna?

189
00:09:17,416 --> 00:09:20,125
I’m Angelica, not Donna.

190
00:09:20,208 --> 00:09:22,083
Are you a human,

191
00:09:22,166 --> 00:09:23,375
or an Automata?

192
00:09:23,458 --> 00:09:25,041
I am human.

193
00:09:25,125 --> 00:09:28,291
Angelica Klein.
I am a researcher.

194
00:09:28,375 --> 00:09:30,291
I can’t be anyone else.

195
00:09:30,375 --> 00:09:32,500
And no one else can be me!

196
00:09:32,583 --> 00:09:35,750
No one else is
the researcher Angelica Klein!

197
00:09:35,833 --> 00:09:38,583
I must see Angelica through!

198
00:09:39,583 --> 00:09:41,416
[ventilation humming]

199
00:09:42,791 --> 00:09:44,458
[door opens]

200
00:09:46,583 --> 00:09:48,208
[Angelica's voice]
I’ve been waiting.

201
00:09:48,291 --> 00:09:50,791
[ANGELICA]
March 7th, 2055.

202
00:09:50,875 --> 00:09:52,791
Researcher, Angelica Klein.

203
00:09:52,875 --> 00:09:54,500
Experiment day 17.

204
00:09:55,500 --> 00:09:56,916
So, how do you feel right now?

205
00:09:57,000 --> 00:09:59,083
Wait, your voice.
What’re you doing?

206
00:09:59,166 --> 00:10:01,375
I don’t understand.
What do you mean?

207
00:10:01,458 --> 00:10:03,416
Donna. What?

208
00:10:03,500 --> 00:10:04,750
[grimace]

209
00:10:04,833 --> 00:10:06,625
Stop! I am not Donna!

210
00:10:06,708 --> 00:10:09,000
You tell me! How do you feel?

211
00:10:09,083 --> 00:10:10,916
[2058]
Let me think...

212
00:10:12,750 --> 00:10:15,791
I want to see this
experiment through.

213
00:10:15,875 --> 00:10:18,083
I won’t give it up.

214
00:10:18,166 --> 00:10:20,166
I must see Angelica through.

215
00:10:21,208 --> 00:10:23,958
[ANGELICA gasps]
How do you know about that?

216
00:10:24,041 --> 00:10:25,500
[2058]
What do you mean, Donna?

217
00:10:25,583 --> 00:10:28,083
I am Angelica.

218
00:10:28,166 --> 00:10:30,125
Why wouldn’t I know?

219
00:10:30,208 --> 00:10:31,791
Don’t get too upset today,

220
00:10:31,875 --> 00:10:33,708
or the experiment
will be canceled.

221
00:10:33,791 --> 00:10:34,750
It won’t be...

222
00:10:34,833 --> 00:10:36,541
-[BOTH] Canceled!
-[gasp]

223
00:10:36,625 --> 00:10:39,625
If you don’t get a grip
on yourself, Donna,

224
00:10:39,708 --> 00:10:41,583
then it most definitely will be!

225
00:10:41,666 --> 00:10:43,458
I am not complete.

226
00:10:43,541 --> 00:10:45,125
Show me more of your insides.

227
00:10:45,208 --> 00:10:47,958
Your panic, your anxiety,
your fear!

228
00:10:48,041 --> 00:10:49,458
-[gasp]
-Everything!

229
00:10:49,541 --> 00:10:51,958
Give me more of Angelica!

230
00:10:52,041 --> 00:10:54,416
[ANGELICA screaming]

231
00:10:54,500 --> 00:10:56,208
♪

232
00:10:56,291 --> 00:10:57,583
Stop, Donna.

233
00:10:57,666 --> 00:11:00,208
-Calm down.
-[grunt, gasp]

234
00:11:01,208 --> 00:11:02,750
My plugs have come loose.

235
00:11:03,750 --> 00:11:05,666
-Let’s get rid of this, too.
-[snip]

236
00:11:07,791 --> 00:11:09,250
Does it hurt?

237
00:11:09,333 --> 00:11:11,583
I don’t understand
that very well, either.

238
00:11:11,666 --> 00:11:14,541
Then allow me to teach you!

239
00:11:14,625 --> 00:11:16,416
-[scream]
-[slice]

240
00:11:16,500 --> 00:11:18,916
[panting]

241
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:21,583
[ANGELICA screams]

242
00:11:21,666 --> 00:11:22,750
[grunting]

243
00:11:22,833 --> 00:11:23,833
[clatter]

244
00:11:25,208 --> 00:11:26,250
[grunt]

245
00:11:27,250 --> 00:11:28,375
-[stab]
-[ANGELICA screams]

246
00:11:29,791 --> 00:11:31,791
-[crunch]
-[ANGELICA screaming]

247
00:11:31,875 --> 00:11:33,750
-[slice]
-[ANGELICA wailing]

248
00:11:33,833 --> 00:11:35,125
[crunch]

249
00:11:44,833 --> 00:11:46,500
[ANDREI panting]

250
00:11:46,583 --> 00:11:49,958
Hey, what’re you doing,
Donna? Stop!

251
00:11:50,041 --> 00:11:52,125
I’m your employer,
y-you remember that, right?

252
00:11:52,208 --> 00:11:54,083
This body is mine,

253
00:11:54,166 --> 00:11:56,083
and no one else’s.

254
00:11:56,166 --> 00:11:58,291
Fire! Now!

255
00:11:58,375 --> 00:12:00,500
-Kill her!
-[gunfire]

256
00:12:00,583 --> 00:12:03,208
-[whimper]
-[DONNA] I will purge you.

257
00:12:03,291 --> 00:12:05,416
You crazy bitch!

258
00:12:05,500 --> 00:12:07,541
-[grunting]
-[hitting]

259
00:12:07,625 --> 00:12:09,250
-[slicing]
-[groaning]

260
00:12:09,333 --> 00:12:11,291
[whimpering]

261
00:12:11,375 --> 00:12:13,333
-[screaming]
-[GUARD] Damn you!

262
00:12:13,416 --> 00:12:14,625
-[slash]
-[grunt]

263
00:12:14,708 --> 00:12:17,000
[whimpering]

264
00:12:18,041 --> 00:12:20,125
[DONNA]
I won’t let anyone steal it.

265
00:12:20,208 --> 00:12:21,833
Never!

266
00:12:21,916 --> 00:12:24,916
[ANDREI screaming]

267
00:12:27,041 --> 00:12:29,541
[WOMAN, overlapping]
Clockwise. Anti-clockwise.

268
00:12:32,416 --> 00:12:34,916
♪

269
00:12:50,791 --> 00:12:52,166
Hold it!

270
00:12:52,250 --> 00:12:54,375
You’re not authorized to
pass through this gate!

271
00:12:54,458 --> 00:12:57,375
I thought that Yetz was
a town open to anyone.

272
00:12:57,458 --> 00:12:59,666
All in the name of
scientific advancement.

273
00:12:59,750 --> 00:13:01,416
That’s right.

274
00:13:01,500 --> 00:13:02,791
But it’s also our
duty to protect

275
00:13:02,875 --> 00:13:04,833
the knowledge
gathered here. Always.

276
00:13:05,833 --> 00:13:08,458
So nobody may enter or leave
at this time of day.

277
00:13:09,458 --> 00:13:11,416
-That’s great.
-Yeah.

278
00:13:11,500 --> 00:13:13,000
Well...

279
00:13:16,291 --> 00:13:17,666
[sigh]

280
00:13:18,666 --> 00:13:20,125
-[MARLENE] Wait.
-[DERRIDA] Hmm?

281
00:13:20,208 --> 00:13:21,666
Doctor?

282
00:13:22,666 --> 00:13:24,208
He can come in.

283
00:13:24,291 --> 00:13:25,875
That’s Derrida Yvain.

284
00:13:26,875 --> 00:13:29,083
I’ll be happy to speak
to a former student.

285
00:13:30,083 --> 00:13:32,250
[MARLENE] We can’t open
the gate until morning.

286
00:13:32,333 --> 00:13:34,250
You’ll have to leave
the car outside.

287
00:13:34,333 --> 00:13:36,708
And you there, sir. Who are you?

288
00:13:36,791 --> 00:13:38,583
[VIDAUX]
His bodyguard, I guess.

289
00:13:38,666 --> 00:13:40,791
I’ll wait until morning, thanks.

290
00:13:40,875 --> 00:13:42,750
♪

291
00:13:45,250 --> 00:13:47,583
Wait! I’m coming, too!

292
00:13:49,625 --> 00:13:51,416
Given your appearance,
I suppose it’s true

293
00:13:51,500 --> 00:13:53,041
that you were
asleep for 10 years.

294
00:13:53,125 --> 00:13:55,625
Mage told you about that?

295
00:13:55,708 --> 00:13:57,208
-[MARLENE] Yes.
-[grunt]

296
00:13:57,291 --> 00:13:58,500
So, is she here?

297
00:13:58,583 --> 00:14:00,458
She was, but...

298
00:14:00,541 --> 00:14:03,250
she’s not in the city anymore.

299
00:14:05,375 --> 00:14:07,500
[DERRIDA]
Do you know where she went?

300
00:14:12,041 --> 00:14:14,000
♪

301
00:14:14,083 --> 00:14:16,750
Professor Marlene of
Yetz Engineering College?

302
00:14:16,833 --> 00:14:20,125
Apparently, she was
Derrida Yvain’s instructor.

303
00:14:20,208 --> 00:14:23,541
And now she leads the defense
force against the DZs.

304
00:14:23,625 --> 00:14:26,500
So, it’s definitely
about the patch file.

305
00:14:26,583 --> 00:14:27,833
And our status?

306
00:14:27,916 --> 00:14:29,750
[HUND]
We can set out tomorrow morning.

307
00:14:29,833 --> 00:14:31,875
That’s cutting it close.

308
00:14:31,958 --> 00:14:33,750
The town will be destroyed
by a missile attack

309
00:14:33,833 --> 00:14:35,166
in just two days.

310
00:14:35,250 --> 00:14:37,458
And there is nothing
they can do about it!

311
00:14:37,541 --> 00:14:38,916
[air rushing]

312
00:14:45,666 --> 00:14:48,625
[MARLENE] The first time I
talked to Mage was 10 years ago.

313
00:14:48,708 --> 00:14:50,708
At Nathan’s funeral.

314
00:14:50,791 --> 00:14:52,333
-[DERRIDA gasps]
-You were there?

315
00:14:53,458 --> 00:14:55,250
[MARLENE]
Naturally.

316
00:14:55,333 --> 00:14:57,875
Nathan and I
corresponded frequently.

317
00:14:57,958 --> 00:15:01,625
And that day, Mage came
to me asking for help

318
00:15:01,708 --> 00:15:03,625
in perfecting the Trout Theory.

319
00:15:03,708 --> 00:15:05,291
I see.

320
00:15:05,375 --> 00:15:07,916
[MARLENE] But, there was
no way for an 8-year-old

321
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:11,125
to do anything with that
information, even with my help.

322
00:15:11,208 --> 00:15:13,750
I didn’t take her
seriously at all.

323
00:15:13,833 --> 00:15:15,416
Not back then...

324
00:15:15,500 --> 00:15:17,208
[YURI]
But afterwards?

325
00:15:17,291 --> 00:15:18,375
[MARLENE]
Yes.

326
00:15:19,958 --> 00:15:21,250
Mage came to me.

327
00:15:21,333 --> 00:15:24,291
It was just about
six months ago.

328
00:15:24,375 --> 00:15:25,875
[DERRIDA]
What did she say?

329
00:15:26,875 --> 00:15:28,833
[MARLENE] She’d come to
a near-perfect understanding

330
00:15:28,916 --> 00:15:31,083
of the Trout Theory on her own.

331
00:15:31,166 --> 00:15:34,000
However,
in order to complete it,

332
00:15:34,083 --> 00:15:36,958
she wanted to see the documents
you’d left at the school.

333
00:15:37,041 --> 00:15:38,041
At her request,

334
00:15:39,041 --> 00:15:40,250
I showed them to her.

335
00:15:41,250 --> 00:15:44,291
But why? The Trout Theory
has dangerous side-effects!

336
00:15:44,375 --> 00:15:46,708
I know that, of course.

337
00:15:46,791 --> 00:15:48,291
And Mage knew it, too.

338
00:15:48,375 --> 00:15:50,250
[gasp]
Even so.

339
00:15:50,333 --> 00:15:51,833
We still have to stop her.

340
00:15:51,916 --> 00:15:54,583
You may be
the Trout Theory’s developer,

341
00:15:55,583 --> 00:15:58,458
but it doesn’t belong
to just you anymore.

342
00:15:59,458 --> 00:16:01,208
I guess not.

343
00:16:01,291 --> 00:16:03,541
Listen to me, Derrida.

344
00:16:03,625 --> 00:16:05,416
Five years ago, a study of mine

345
00:16:05,500 --> 00:16:08,166
culminated in
a terrible tragedy.

346
00:16:08,250 --> 00:16:09,083
Which study?

347
00:16:09,166 --> 00:16:10,333
♪

348
00:16:10,416 --> 00:16:11,708
[MARLENE]
It was an experiment to create

349
00:16:11,791 --> 00:16:14,791
an Automata DZ-model
with its own personality.

350
00:16:14,875 --> 00:16:16,958
I’ve never heard
of such a thing!

351
00:16:17,041 --> 00:16:19,083
-Do you mean...
-Yes.

352
00:16:19,166 --> 00:16:20,416
You may remember.

353
00:16:20,500 --> 00:16:22,208
It was an original
research theme of mine.

354
00:16:22,291 --> 00:16:25,291
Successfully completing
a model with a personality

355
00:16:25,375 --> 00:16:28,333
would greatly expand
the possibilities for Automata.

356
00:16:29,333 --> 00:16:31,708
But, after the military DZs
went berserk,

357
00:16:31,791 --> 00:16:34,416
the research was
deemed dangerous.

358
00:16:34,500 --> 00:16:36,291
I had to distance
myself from the work

359
00:16:36,375 --> 00:16:38,208
in order to preserve
my position.

360
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:43,666
[sigh]
After that,

361
00:16:43,750 --> 00:16:46,125
the research was taken on
by another organization.

362
00:16:46,208 --> 00:16:47,375
Watch this.

363
00:16:47,458 --> 00:16:49,708
Here’s the record
of that experiment.

364
00:16:49,791 --> 00:16:50,750
-[static]
-[DERRIDA] Huh?

365
00:16:50,833 --> 00:16:53,833
♪

366
00:16:56,791 --> 00:16:57,625
[BOTH gasp]

367
00:17:05,250 --> 00:17:07,791
[ANGELICA]
March 7th, 2055.

368
00:17:07,875 --> 00:17:09,833
Researcher, Angelica Klein.

369
00:17:09,916 --> 00:17:11,458
Experiment day 17.

370
00:17:11,541 --> 00:17:13,083
[2058, robotic] So,
how do you feel right now?

371
00:17:13,166 --> 00:17:14,875
[MARLENE] The people who
took over my research

372
00:17:14,958 --> 00:17:16,583
threw caution to the wind,

373
00:17:16,666 --> 00:17:19,208
in the pursuit of
achieving faster results.

374
00:17:19,291 --> 00:17:21,958
The DZ began to show
inclinations of thought

375
00:17:22,041 --> 00:17:24,791
that couldn’t properly
be called a personality.

376
00:17:24,875 --> 00:17:27,541
But changes occurred in
the researcher, Angelica, too.

377
00:17:28,708 --> 00:17:31,708
♪

378
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:37,375
Derrida Yvain.

379
00:17:49,250 --> 00:17:50,583
-[scream]
-[smash]

380
00:17:53,166 --> 00:17:55,166
[panting]

381
00:17:57,708 --> 00:17:59,291
[grunt, sigh]

382
00:18:00,333 --> 00:18:02,416
[ANGELICA]
I won’t let anyone steal it.

383
00:18:03,416 --> 00:18:07,291
[MARLENE] After that, Angelica
set fire to the facility.

384
00:18:08,958 --> 00:18:11,666
Several bodies were found
in the charred remains,

385
00:18:11,750 --> 00:18:15,250
except Angelica, and DZNA 2058

386
00:18:15,333 --> 00:18:17,583
-disappeared without a trace.
-[static, beep]

387
00:18:19,416 --> 00:18:21,166
As you can see,
the result of abandoning

388
00:18:21,250 --> 00:18:23,250
my research was tragic.

389
00:18:24,875 --> 00:18:26,916
Um, wasn’t that...

390
00:18:28,208 --> 00:18:29,416
No doubt about it.

391
00:18:31,291 --> 00:18:33,083
-[DERRIDA] It’s Donna.
-Donna?

392
00:18:33,166 --> 00:18:36,041
Which means she was
a victim of DZ research.

393
00:18:37,041 --> 00:18:39,583
That’s why she’s so
determined to kill me.

394
00:18:39,666 --> 00:18:40,750
[sigh]

395
00:18:40,833 --> 00:18:42,333
Maybe I deserve this?

396
00:18:42,416 --> 00:18:43,833
Derrida...

397
00:18:43,916 --> 00:18:46,583
[DERRIDA] The Trout Theory
and the DZs, too.

398
00:18:46,666 --> 00:18:49,875
The research I’ve taken part
in produces nothing but misery!

399
00:18:49,958 --> 00:18:53,833
A person like me should've
never chased his dreams at all!

400
00:18:53,916 --> 00:18:55,333
You’re wrong.

401
00:18:55,416 --> 00:18:57,000
-[YURI] Huh?
-[MARLENE] As scientists,

402
00:18:57,083 --> 00:19:00,291
it's not a mistake to have
dreams and try to realize them.

403
00:19:00,375 --> 00:19:01,583
It’s our duty.

404
00:19:01,666 --> 00:19:03,000
[DERRIDA gasps]

405
00:19:03,083 --> 00:19:05,541
Derrida, I have regrets.

406
00:19:05,625 --> 00:19:07,125
♪

407
00:19:07,208 --> 00:19:10,166
If I hadn’t abandoned my
research just to save myself,

408
00:19:10,250 --> 00:19:13,125
then maybe I could've
prevented that tragedy.

409
00:19:15,500 --> 00:19:17,291
There’s no denying
that our experiments

410
00:19:17,375 --> 00:19:20,250
will sometimes produce results
we never could've predicted.

411
00:19:20,333 --> 00:19:22,208
Both for good and for bad.

412
00:19:23,375 --> 00:19:25,750
But if you or I have
done anything wrong,

413
00:19:25,833 --> 00:19:28,333
it was in turning our
backs on our research,

414
00:19:28,416 --> 00:19:30,125
not in daring
to dream at all.

415
00:19:30,208 --> 00:19:33,208
Are you saying that because
I abandoned the Trout Theory,

416
00:19:33,291 --> 00:19:34,291
Mage is...

417
00:19:34,375 --> 00:19:35,541
[MARLENE]
You can still make it.

418
00:19:35,625 --> 00:19:36,458
[DERRIDA gasps]

419
00:19:40,625 --> 00:19:41,875
[DERRIDA]
Hmm?

420
00:19:43,125 --> 00:19:46,500
This machine will block DZ
sensors to help you avoid them.

421
00:19:46,583 --> 00:19:47,750
It’s a jamming device.

422
00:19:48,750 --> 00:19:51,166
This technology is
what’s keeping Yetz safe.

423
00:19:51,250 --> 00:19:54,416
This is Cassiel’s!

424
00:19:54,500 --> 00:19:55,583
[MARLENE]
Yes.

425
00:19:55,666 --> 00:19:57,666
Mage left it behind for us.

426
00:19:59,916 --> 00:20:02,416
You see? Technology
really can create results

427
00:20:02,500 --> 00:20:04,791
you never dreamed. Derrida...

428
00:20:05,791 --> 00:20:08,166
Don’t turn your back
on what you believe in.

429
00:20:08,250 --> 00:20:10,125
No matter what.

430
00:20:10,208 --> 00:20:12,000
[sigh]

431
00:20:12,083 --> 00:20:14,791
♪

432
00:20:19,958 --> 00:20:22,375
[NATHAN] “What is the key
to traveling through time?”

433
00:20:22,458 --> 00:20:23,833
-Huh.
-[yawn]

434
00:20:23,916 --> 00:20:25,583
Marlene asks you for a thesis,

435
00:20:25,666 --> 00:20:27,791
and you give her something that
reads more like science fiction.

436
00:20:27,875 --> 00:20:30,500
You do realize she’s at
her wit’s end, don’t you?

437
00:20:30,583 --> 00:20:31,958
Look, man.

438
00:20:32,041 --> 00:20:34,125
The reason she’s upset
isn’t because of me.

439
00:20:34,208 --> 00:20:35,958
The problem is those
academic bigwigs

440
00:20:36,041 --> 00:20:37,666
that don’t understand my thesis.

441
00:20:37,750 --> 00:20:39,208
[chuckle]
Okay, fine,

442
00:20:39,291 --> 00:20:41,708
but that doesn’t
really help either way.

443
00:20:41,791 --> 00:20:43,208
Mmm?

444
00:20:49,166 --> 00:20:51,291
[laughing]

445
00:20:52,416 --> 00:20:53,666
[chuckle]

446
00:21:00,791 --> 00:21:01,791
Huh?

447
00:21:06,750 --> 00:21:08,583
Nathan...

448
00:21:08,666 --> 00:21:09,583
[picks up paper]

449
00:21:10,583 --> 00:21:13,083
[DERRIDA]
“December 15th, 2050.

450
00:21:14,166 --> 00:21:16,916
Researcher, Nathan Bilstein.”

451
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:20,750
♪

452
00:21:28,291 --> 00:21:30,583
No way. This is my design
for an experiment,

453
00:21:31,583 --> 00:21:34,291
at the Effelsberg
electromagnetic telescope.

454
00:21:35,416 --> 00:21:37,833
A quiet place. Hold on.

455
00:21:37,916 --> 00:21:38,916
That’s it!

456
00:23:13,916 --> 00:23:16,541
♪

457
00:23:16,625 --> 00:23:19,875
[NATHAN, on speaker]
Researcher, Nathan Bilstein.

458
00:23:19,958 --> 00:23:21,875
As expected, it’s difficult

459
00:23:21,958 --> 00:23:24,416
to relive experiences
from the past.

460
00:23:24,500 --> 00:23:27,375
Even the memories that
remain clearest in the mind

461
00:23:27,458 --> 00:23:31,583
are vulnerable to being
distorted by strong emotions.

462
00:23:41,500 --> 00:23:42,708
[groaning]

463
00:23:43,708 --> 00:23:45,208
Derrida...

